+## 1. Executive Summary
+
+Dataslope's three SQL playgrounds (SQLite, Postgres, DuckDB) share an impressive amount of infrastructure: the editor, tab bar, results table, schema sidebar, query history, and most dialogs are the same React components reused across engines. That sharing pays off in baseline consistency — but it has also produced a long tail of UX bugs and inconsistencies that show up as soon as a user does anything beyond `SELECT * FROM …`.
+
+The most important themes:
+
+1. **The shared "SQLite-flavored" defaults leak across engines.** Hard-coded strings ("Loading SQLite engine…"), SQLite-only error hints, and SQLite-style truncation messages appear inside Postgres and DuckDB sessions (see [§5.1](#51-first-load-and-engine-boot-ux), [§5.7](#57-invalid-queries--error-states)). This breaks the illusion that each playground is a first-class environment.
+
+2. **Engine-boot failures are a dead end.** If the CDN-hosted WASM bundle fails to load (which is trivially reproducible in restrictive networks — and is the actual experience inside the audit sandbox), the user sees an enormous title-stamp loading screen with a tiny single-line error at the bottom, no retry button, and disabled Import/Export buttons with no tooltip explaining why ([§5.1](#51-first-load-and-engine-boot-ux)).
+
+3. **Destructive actions are too quiet.** `DROP TABLE` in Postgres silently adds `CASCADE`, and `TRUNCATE` silently adds `RESTART IDENTITY CASCADE`, but the confirmation dialogs say nothing about cascade effects or dependent objects. There is no "type the table name to confirm" affordance for dangerous operations ([§5.4](#54-dropping-a-table--destructive-actions)).
+
+4. **The Create Table dialog is the most-used metadata flow and has the most friction.** The 13-column wide table layout doesn't degrade on narrow viewports, the type combobox only shows entries matching whatever text is already in the field (so a user who types `int` then opens the dropdown sees a single entry and assumes there are no other types), Escape doesn't close the dialog reliably, and there is no SQL DDL preview ([§5.2](#52-creating-a-new-table--adding-columns)).
+
+5. **Inline cell editing has no type awareness.** Every cell — JSON, JSONB, BYTEA, TIMESTAMPTZ, UUID, arrays, STRUCTs — is edited through a single-line plain text input. Pending edits aren't applied until the user notices and clicks a separate "Commit" button. Once committed, there is no per-cell undo within the session ([§5.3](#53-inline-cell-editing-for-non-trivial-types)).
+
+6. **No creation/edit UI for triggers, indexes, views, or constraints.** Users can _see_ DDL for these objects and they can drop them, but to create or modify one they must drop into raw SQL — which makes the rich sidebar tree feel like a read-only museum ([§5.5](#55-triggers-indexes-and-views), [§5.6](#56-editing-constraints-defaults-relationships)).
+
+7. **Errors lose their context.** Multi-statement errors don't tell the user which statement failed; the editor does not highlight the offending line/column; partial results from preceding statements are discarded; and the error overlay auto-dismisses after ~3 seconds, which is often before the user has read it ([§5.7](#57-invalid-queries--error-states)).
+
+8. **Import / export parity across engines is poor.** SQLite has CSV/JSON/Parquet/XLSX/.db import; Postgres only has .sql dumps; DuckDB requires the user to write `read_csv(...)` SQL by hand even though the engine itself supports those formats natively ([§5.9](#59-import--export)).
+
+The good news: most of these are fixable without architectural surgery, since the shared `SqlPlayground` / `SqlPlaygroundShell` / `ResultView` components are the right place to centralize the fixes.
